  {
    "id": 1621359391868,
    "type": "text",
    "content": "\"<h1>Condition</h1>\""
  },
  {
    "id": 1636662065710,
    "type": "grid",
    "content": [
      [
        {
          "id": 1636662074274,
          "type": "text",
          "content": "\"<h2>Live Hard Coral Cover</h2><p><span style=\\\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\\\">Overall, there has been a 5% loss of coral cover in the RSGA region since monitoring began in 1997, though it has not been a consistent decline.&nbsp;By&nbsp;2002 coral cover declined from 36.1% to 32.3%&nbsp;as a consequence of&nbsp;the mass coral bleaching event that occurred in 1998, which&nbsp;affected&nbsp;one-third of&nbsp;the region’s reefs.&nbsp;During the next six years, coral cover almost recovered to pre-1998 levels, reaching 35.3% in 2008, but progressively declined again to 30.9%&nbsp;by&nbsp;2016 . Since 2016, average coral cover has increased again to 34.3% in 2019.&nbsp;&nbsp;Coral cover loss has been driven by thermal stress as well as local threats.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\""
        }
      ],
      [
        {
          "id": 1636662077004,
          "type": "text",
          "content": "\"<h2>Algae Cover</h2><p><span style=\\\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);\\\">The average cover of algae on coral reefs in the region&nbsp;is generally low.&nbsp;Between 1997 and 2006, the cover of algae exhibited a similar trend to that of coral cover, with an initial decline from 8.6% in 1997 to 4.5% in 2002, which was followed by a progressive increase to 8.4% in 2006. The cover of algae varied little during the next six&nbsp;years but&nbsp;increased from 7.8% in 2012 to 14.7% in 2019, almost doubling the&nbsp;amount&nbsp;of algae on reefs in the region during that time.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\""
        }
      ]
    ]
  },
